 popular. It\u2019s a dream plastic car, and melts away in\nthe hot weather. Metal men the nation over, have written in for\ncopies of the cartoon cl the \u201cPlasticar\u201d \u2014it s great to show their\ncustomers.\nWhile they have a tendency to decry the use of plastics for\nanything and everything, they don't hesitate to recommend them\nwhen they have sufficient strength will contribute to lower\nproduction costs.\nUnique are their model shops\u2014one on Milwaukee and the\nother on Ch* s rry street. In these, full size moekups are built up so\nthat the customer can see just how his product will look when\ncompleted.\nIn these shops, wood and clay models of everything from an\nelectric iron to a 10-ton truck have been turned out. The manufae-\ngsL\nTn+\ngj|!\n||P* i fefr ,aT\\\nP+S, H\nHI\nJm\nThe kitchen side of a molded kitchen-bathroom unit.\nturers like the idea and Sundberg and Ferar feel that the shops\nmore than pay for themselves in good will.\nStrangely enough. 80 per cent of their business comes from\noutside Detroit and they number among their clients, such firms\nas De Vilhiss, Square D, Sears* Crosley, Federal Motor, Colonial\nRadio and Swartzbaugh (Evcrhot line) Mfg.\nBecause of the number of Eastern clients, they decided to\nopen offices in New York City recently. They were all set to sign\na lease with the Empire State Building but on the morning the floor\nplans of the 7Sth floor armed, an army pilot in a bomber altered\nthe layout. They\u2019re looking for a less vulnerable location.\nJust to give you an idea of the wide range of products, they\nhave on their thawing boards, I saw a streamlined double decker\nstreet car. an automatic phonograph record changer, a kitchen\nunit with the bathroom unit built on the back for a package building\ncombination and. of course, ultra modern automobiles.\nCrawford Appointed\nBy Founders Group\nW. B. Crawford, president of\nthe Atlas Foundry Co. and Detroit\narea director of the Gray Iron\nFounders\u2019 